salaries <- read.csv("salaries.csv")

#In first step of data cleaning

Here we subset Salary.Currency and Salary, becuse there were different currencies however Salaary.in.USD column is considers unified information. Our data was a timeseries data covering data points from 2020 to 2023. As for convenience of our model, and considering requirements, we chose single year so made it as cross-sectional data. After grouping datapoints with relevant dplyr package functions, most data points were in 2023 so we keep data points from 2023. # # # # # # # # #Convert relevant variables to categorical variable

unique_categories <- unique(salaries$Job.Title)
experience <- unique(salaries$Experience.Level)
expertise <- unique(salaries$Expertise.Level)
location <- unique(salaries$Company.Location)
residence <- unique(salaries$Employee.Residence)
size <- unique(salaries$Company.Size)

Converting variables were necessary step, as initially they were created as character or numeric data however their context was not matching their variable type. As first step we take uniques of each variables to have a cleaan data for converting # # # # # # # # #Converting factors

salaries$Job.Title <- factor(salaries$Job.Title, levels = unique_categories)
salaries$Employment_Type_Dummy <- ifelse(salaries$Employment.Type == "Full-Time", 1, 0)
salaries$Experience.Level <- factor(salaries$Experience.Level, levels = experience)
salaries$Expertise.Level <- factor(salaries$Expertise.Level, levels = expertise)
salaries$Company.Size <- factor(salaries$Company.Size, levels = size)
#is.na(salaries)

Above mentioned converting waasa simple as exact values were able to be considered for levels # # # # # # # # #Further Convertations

Additional to above mentioned categorization, we categorized Company Location, and Employee Residence based on them being OECD countries. This step is necessary because without it in later steps having too many categories will cause a problem in PCA. Categorization based on whether being OECD is economically logical, as these countries share similarities. # # # # # # # # #Further Convertations

# Adding columns based on the presence of specific words in the job title
salaries$Has_Big <- ifelse(grepl("big", tolower(salaries$Job.Title)), 1, 0)
salaries$Has_Manager <- ifelse(grepl("Manager", tolower(salaries$Job.Title)), 1, 0)
salaries$Has_Data <- ifelse(grepl("data", tolower(salaries$Job.Title)), 1, 0)
# Defining a function to categorize job titles
categorize_title <- function(title) {
  if (grepl("data engineer|big data|etl", tolower(title))) {
    return("Data Engineer")
  } else if (grepl("data scientist|lead data|principal data|applied data", tolower(title))) {
    return("Data Scientist")
  } else if (grepl("machine learning|ml|deep learning|nlp|computer vision", tolower(title))) {
    return("Machine Learning")
  } else if (grepl("data analyst|bi analyst|bi data|business data|data quality|data operations", tolower(title))) {
    return("Analyst")
  } else if (grepl("manager|director|head of data|lead", tolower(title))) {
    return("Manager/Director")
  } else if (grepl("research", tolower(title))) {
    return("Research")
  } else if (grepl("business intelligence|bi developer", tolower(title))) {
    return("Business Intelligence")
  } else if (grepl("^ai$|ai | ai|artificial intelligence", tolower(title))) {
    return("AI")
  } else if (grepl("architect", tolower(title))) {
    return("Architect")
  } else if (grepl("consultant", tolower(title))) {
    return("Consultant")
  } else if (grepl("specialist", tolower(title))) {
    return("Specialist")
  } else {
    return("Other")
  }
}

# Here we apply the categorization function to the job titles
salaries$Job.Category <- sapply(salaries$Job.Title, categorize_title)

Now here we will categorize Job Titles. First we added three coolumns based on if there is word Big, Data or Manager in title, we will later check if it is an affect based on our research. After cross-tabulation we see that experience nd expertise level consider multicollinearity risk so we will drop one of them. Last two rows of above-mentioned section is to check if there is case of potential information loss in case for drop, which is not, as results exactly match. # # # # # # # # #Descriptive Statistics

From summary of our data, we see that most of our employees have full-time employment, and their experience level is mostly senior. There is huge salary variance. Most of our employees and employers are in OECD countries, however these variables are not mirroring each other. # # # # # # # # #Visualization

# Histogram for Salary in USD
ggplot(salaries, aes(x = `Salary.in.USD`)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5000, fill = "skyblue", color = "black", alpha = 0.7) +

From Histogram of Distribution of Salary in USD, we can see that our data is slightly right-skewed, which means most of our data points are in left side from mean, or less we could see this information in summary section as well, by comparing numbers. We believe that data contains a lot of valuable information, as for young researchers its interesting to analyze reasons for these deviations. # # # # # # # # #Bar plots

# Aggregate data by Job Category to calculate average salaries
avg_salaries <- salaries %>%
  group_by(`Job.Category`) %>%
  summarize(Avg_Salary = mean(`Salary.in.USD`))

# Bar plot for average salaries by Job Category
ggplot(avg_salaries, aes(x = `Job.Category`, y = Avg_Salary)) +

Above we displayed 3 histograms, 1st is distribution of job categories based on their frequency. We se that job categories also vary, instead of concentrating in one category. There are still differences between minimum and maximum frequencies but we believe our categorization is sufficient, as to much generalizing might effect results negatively and cause for potential information loss. Another supportive argument is that, average salaries are close to each other, so our data is homogenous and we successfully combines similar jobs together. However, there is still difference between average numbers, so it shows that from information loss aspect we were also sucessful, and achieved to keep differences. Last histogram shows experience level, and is in line with our previous statement about experience. # # # # # # # # #Storing results of data cleaning in new dataset

new_salaries <- salaries %>% 
                select(Salary.in.USD, Employment_Type_Dummy, Experience.Level, 
                       Company.Size, Location_Dummy, Residency_Dummy, Has_Big, 
                       Has_Data, Job.Category)
colnames(new_salaries) <- gsub("\\.", "_", colnames(new_salaries))

#Now we create new dataset where we keep cleaned data. We dropped Has_Manager because it was irrelavent as there was no job title with word Manager, we also dropped Expertise level, as above-mentioned results proved that they are mirroring Experience.Level variable. Meanwhile we made new data set with newly created categories. Here we also convert “.” to “_” as in advance modeling it cause errors # # # # # # # # #Data splitting

set.seed(123)  # Setting seed ensures reproducibility

# Splitting data into training and testing sets
index <- createDataPartition(new_salaries$`Salary_in_USD`, p = 0.7, list = FALSE)
train_data <- new_salaries[index, ]
test_data  <- new_salaries[-index, ]

Data Splitting this will be vital for further modeling steps. By choosing 0.7 for p, we allocate 70% of our data for training, and 30% for testing. We choose this approach to have sufficient amount of data for testing, meanwhile making ability of training optimal. Ofcourse this selection, could be matter for discussion. # # # # # # # # #Model Building (Simple Models)

# Linear Regression
lm_model <- lm(`Salary_in_USD` ~ ., data = train_data)
lm_predictions <- predict(lm_model, newdata = test_data)
lm_predictions_train <- predict(lm_model, newdata = train_data)
summary(lm_model)

Linear Regression- The median residual value is -7480, indicating that the model’s median prediction was $7,480 higher than the actual salary. Employment_Type_Dummy has a positive coefficient, indicating that this type of employment generally leads to higher salaries. Experience levels such as “Entry” and “Mid” have negative coefficients, suggesting that these levels earn less compared to the baseline (probably “Senior”). Conversely, the “Executive” level has a positive coefficient, indicating higher salaries.Company size impacts the salary, with “Small” companies typically paying less. The Location_Dummy1 and Residency_Dummy1 variables, while not statistically significant at a 0.05 level, indicate potential salary differences based on location and residency. The presence of the word “Big” (Has_Big) in job titles/descriptions seems to decrease the salary, while “Data” (Has_Data) has a similar negative effect but is statistically significant at the 0.05 level. Various job categories have different impacts on the salary. Most of them are not statistically significant, but their presence provides insights into potential salary variations across roles. The Multiple R-squared value is 0.2669, meaning that the model explains approximately 26.69% of the variance in salaries. This suggests there’s a lot of unexplained variance, and while the model has some predictive power, there’s room for improvement. The F-statistic and its associated p-value test the overall significance of the model. The extremely low p-value (< 2.2e-16) suggests that the model is statistically significant and that at least some predictors help in predicting the salary. The Adjusted R-squared value is slightly lower than the R-squared, accounting for the number of predictors in the model. It indicates that about 25.66% of the variance in salaries is explained by the model after adjusting for the number of predictors. Tree Model- The “CP” (Complexity Parameter) values tell us the relative importance of each split. Smaller CP values indicate less important splits. The tree is built until the CP value decreases below a specified threshold, which is 0.01 for us. The most critical predictor in this tree is Experience_Level, accounting for 44% of the splits’ importance which is in line with linear regression, followed by Job_Category (34%) and Has_Data (10%). Its result about Job Category is interesting as significance level for this variable was pretty less in linear regression. Node number 1 is the root node containing all 1517 observations. The primary split is made on Experience_Level, dividing the data into left (Node 2) and right (Node 3) children nodes. Node 2 further splits on Job_Category, and Node 3 splits on the same. Nodes like 5, 6, 8, 9, 14, and 15 are terminal nodes or leaves. The mean value in these nodes represents the predicted Salary_in_USD for observations that end up in that node. As backup rules for making a split if the primary rule does not apply (e.g. due to missing data). For example, if Experience_Level is missing in Node 1, the surrogate split Residency_Dummy could be used. The rel error represents the proportion of total sum of squares remaining in the data before the split, and the xerror (cross-validated error) is an estimate of prediction error. A lower xerror indicates better predictive accuracy. The xstd gives an estimate of the standard error of the xerror. # # # # #

MAE is the average of the absolute differences between the predicted and actual values. It gives an idea of how wrong the predictions were. RMSE gives an idea of how concentrated the data is around the line of best fit. A lower MAE indicates a better fit to the data. There is no huge difference between these MAE and RMSE, so we can not say that there is presence of large errors. Considering MAE and RMSE being proportionally less than Decision tree, results show that Lineaar Regression is better fit for the data than Decision tree, it not only predicts better but has fewer instances for large prediction errors. # # # # #

train_data_dummies <- model.matrix(Salary_in_USD ~ . - 1, data = train_data) # '- 1' removes intercept
test_data_dummies <- model.matrix(Salary_in_USD ~ . - 1, data = test_data)
scaled_train_data <- scale(train_data_dummies)
scaled_test_data <- scale(test_data_dummies)
pca_train <- prcomp(scaled_train_data, center = TRUE, scale. = TRUE)
pca_test <- prcomp(scaled_test_data, center = TRUE, scale. = TRUE)
#PCA to Linear Regression 
lm_model_pca <- lm(Salary_in_USD ~ ., data = data.frame(Salary_in_USD = train_data$Salary_in_USD, pca_train$x))
lm_predictions_pca <- predict(lm_model_pca, newdata = data.frame(pca_test$x))
#PCA to Decision Tree
tree_model_pca <- rpart(Salary_in_USD ~ ., data = data.frame(Salary_in_USD = train_data$Salary_in_USD, pca_train$x))
tree_predictions_pca <- predict(tree_model_pca, newdata = data.frame(pca_test$x))
#PCA to Random Forest
rf_model_pca <- randomForest(Salary_in_USD ~ ., data = data.frame(Salary_in_USD = train_data$Salary_in_USD, pca_train$x))
rf_predictions_pca <- predict(rf_model_pca, newdata = data.frame(pca_test$x))
#PCA to Neural Network
library(nnet)
nn_model_pca <- nnet(Salary_in_USD ~ ., data = data.frame(Salary_in_USD = train_data$Salary_in_USD, pca_train$x), size = 10, linout = TRUE)

The model.matrix function is used to create dummy variables (also known as one-hot encoding) for the categorical variables in the training and test datasets. The -1 term ensures the intercept column is not added. The data is then standardized using the scale function, which centers and scales the data to have a mean of zero and a standard deviation of one. This step is critical before PCA, as PCA is sensitive to the variances of the initial variables. PCA is performed on both the training and test datasets. This process reduces the dimensionality of the data by capturing the most variance in the least number of principal components. It’s often used to simplify datasets while keeping as much of the original information as possible. A linear regression model is trained using the principal components derived from the PCA. Predictions are then made on the test dataset using this model. A random forest model is trained using the principal components from the PCA. Predictions are then made on the test dataset using this model. The neural network has a single hidden layer with 10 units (size = 10). The linout = TRUE argument indicates that the neural network will perform linear. The “initial value” represents the error before any training. The “final value” shows the error after 100 iterations. The fact that it “stopped after 100 iterations” suggests that the training did not converge to a solution before the maximum number of iterations was reached. # # # # #

Here in this plot we can better see differences on RMSE of models with PCA. As stated above, Linear Regression performed worst among these models, and including its result negatively affect visibility of the illustration so we decided to excluded it. # # # # #
#Compare RMSE for Linear Regression and Neural Networks analysis based on both train and test data

# Comapring 
metrics_df <- data.frame(
  Model = c("Linear Regression", "Decision Trees", "Random Forest", "Neural Network"),
  RMSE_Test = c(lm_rmse, tree_rmse, forest_rmse, neural_rmse),
  RMSE_Train = c(lm_rmse_train, tree_rmse_train, forest_rmse_training, neural_rmsetr)
)

# Reshape the data frame
metrics_df <- metrics_df %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = starts_with("RMSE"), names_to = "Dataset", values_to = "RMSE_Value")

# Create the bar plot with preferred colors
ggplot(metrics_df, aes(x = Model, y = RMSE_Value, fill = Dataset)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge", color = "black") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("red", "blue")) +
  labs(title = "Model Performance Comparison (RMSE)",
       y = "RMSE",
       x = "Model") +
  theme_minimal()

To compare above-mentioned plot with previous one we see that, applying PCA negative impact on all models except Neural Potential reason is that these three are traditional machine learning algorithms that don’t inherently benefit from dimensionality reduction through PCA. PCA can sometimes lead to information loss because it projects the data onto a lower-dimensional space while trying to preserve variance. The decrease in RMSE for the Neural Network suggests that the reduced-dimensional data produced by PCA provides a more suitable input for the network. It’s possible that PCA helped in simplifying the problem or reducing noise in the data, making it easier for the neural network to learn meaningful patterns. # # # # #
#Calculation of Rsquare for models with and without PCA

# For Linear Regression with PCA
lm_r2_pca <- 1 - sum((test_data$Salary_in_USD - lm_predictions_pca)^2) / sum((test_data$Salary_in_USD - mean(test_data$Salary_in_USD))^2)

# For Decision Tree with PCA
tree_r2_pca <- 1 - sum((test_data$Salary_in_USD - tree_predictions_pca)^2) / sum((test_data$Salary_in_USD - mean(test_data$Salary_in_USD))^2)

# For Random Forest with PCA
rf_r2_pca <- 1 - sum((test_data$Salary_in_USD - rf_predictions_pca)^2) / sum((test_data$Salary_in_USD - mean(test_data$Salary_in_USD))^2)

# For Neural Network with PCA
nn_r2_pca <- 1 - sum((test_data$Salary_in_USD - nn_predictions_pca)^2) / sum((test_data$Salary_in_USD - mean(test_data$Salary_in_USD))^2)

# For Linear Regression
lm_r2 <- 1 - sum((test_data$Salary_in_USD - lm_predictions)^2) / sum((test_data$Salary_in_USD - mean(test_data$Salary_in_USD))^2)

# For Decision Tree
tree_r2 <- 1 - sum((test_data$Salary_in_USD - tree_predictions)^2) / sum((test_data$Salary_in_USD - mean(test_data$Salary_in_USD))^2)

# For Random Forest
rf_r2 <- 1 - sum((test_data$Salary_in_USD - rf_predictions)^2) / sum((test_data$Salary_in_USD - mean(test_data$Salary_in_USD))^2)

# For Neural Network
nn_r2 <- 1 - sum((test_data$Salary_in_USD - nn_predictions)^2) / sum((test_data$Salary_in_USD - mean(test_data$Salary_in_USD))^2)
